    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the financial statement notes, here is a detailed breakdown of SpaceX\'s revenue recognition policies, with a focus on intersegment revenue, performance obligations, and segment allocation.\n\n### 1. Overview of Revenue Recognition by Segment\nSpaceX recognizes revenue across three primary segments: **Space, Connectivity, and AI**. The recognition method (over time or at a point in time) and the treatment of performance obligations differ significantly based on the segment and the nature of the contract.\n\n### 2. Space Segment Revenue Recognition\n*   **Revenue Sources:** Launch Services (for deploying customer payloads) and Launch & Development (for developing spacecraft and providing services for government programs).\n*   **Performance Obligations & Recognition:**\n    *   **Launch Services:** Recognized at a **point in time** (upon launch or deployment) because flight hardware is interchangeable and has minimal unique engineering costs. Costs are deferred until launch.\n    *   **Launch & Development:** Recognized **over time** using the **cost-to-cost input method**. This applies when the created asset has no alternative use and there is an enforceable right to payment. Revenue is recorded based on costs incurred to date versus total estimated costs at completion.\n*   **Intersegment Revenue & Capacity Allocation:**\n    *   Launches dedicated to deploying the company\'s own **Starlink satellites do not generate intersegment revenue** for the Space segment.\n    *   Instead, the costs of these internal launches are **capitalized** as part of "Property, plant, and equipment" within the **Connectivity segment** and depreciated over time.\n    *   The company allocates significant launch capacity to its Connectivity segment and expects to do so for its **AI segment in the future**. The Space segment\'s reported revenue reflects only customer-facing activities.\n\n### 3. Connectivity Segment Revenue Recognition\n*   **Revenue Sources:** Broadband and Starlink Mobile services (Consumer & Enterprise), Starshield contracts, and Starlink Kit sales.\n*   **Performance Obligations & Recognition:**\n    *   **Consumer/Enterprise Services:** Contracts typically contain **multiple performance obligations**—(i) broadband services and (ii) the Starlink Kit. The transaction price is allocated based on standalone selling prices.\n        *   *Services:* Recognized **over time** as the customer simultaneously consumes benefits. For fixed-price subscriptions, revenue is recognized ratably; for variable plans, based on data usage. Amounts received in advance are recorded as deferred revenue.\n        *   *Starlink Kit:* Recognized at a **point in time** (upon delivery or installation).\n    *   **Starshield:** Long-term, fixed-price contracts recognized **over time** using the **cost-to-cost input method**, similar to Launch & Development contracts. Significant management judgment is required for cost estimates.\n*   **Deferred Revenue:** Primarily relates to advanced payments for enterprise/government contracts and services.\n\n### 4. AI Segment Revenue Recognition\n*   **Revenue Sources:** Advertising, subscriptions (e.g., X, Grok), data licensing, and API access.\n*   **Performance Obligations & Recognition:**\n    *   **Advertising:** Recognized at a **point in time** when the ad is delivered and user engagement meets criteria. The company acts as **principal** (gross revenue) for direct sales via the X platform and as **agent** (net revenue) for sales through SSP partners.\n    *   **Subscriptions:** Recognized **ratably over the subscription term**.\n    *   **Data Licensing:** May have single or multiple performance obligations. Recognition depends on the arrangement: over time for future IP, point-in-time for historical IP, or ratably for fixed fees. Minimum guarantees are recognized straight-line, with excess royalties recognized over the term.\n    *   **API Services:** Stand-ready obligation recognized either **ratably** (for subscription access) or **as consumed** (for usage-based/token processing).\n\n### 5. Key Judgments and Disclosures\n*   **Cost-to-Cost Method:** Used for long-term contracts in the Space (Launch & Development) and Connectivity (Starshield) segments. Requires significant estimates of total costs, including materials, labor, and technological changes. Changes in estimates are recognized on a cumulative basis.\n*   **Backlog:** As of December 31, 2025, total backlog was **$28.4 billion**, of which $12.1 billion was deferred revenue. Approximately 32% is expected to be recognized within one year.\n*   **Segment Allocation:** Revenue is clearly segregated. For example:\n    *   **Products revenue** (mainly Starlink Kits) is entirely attributable to the **Connectivity** segment.\n    *   **Enterprise & Government revenue** within Connectivity includes Starlink Mobile services.\n    *   **Space segment revenue** excludes all internal constellation launches.\n\nIn summary, SpaceX\'s revenue recognition is tailored to each segment\'s business model, with strict rules preventing intersegment profit recognition for internal launches while carefully allocating capacity across segments. The policies involve significant judgment, particularly for long-term, complex contracts using the cost-to-cost method.',
