 in these excerpts. However, the **"Total Reportable Segments"** figures likely reflect the **net effect after intersegment eliminations** (e.g., the removal of any intersegment revenue or cost allocations). For example:\n     - The Space segment\'s revenue ($619M in Q1 2026) excludes intersegment launch revenue.\n     - The Connectivity segment\'s cost of revenue ($1,651M in Q1 2026) likely includes the capitalized launch costs for Starlink satellites (transferred from the Space segment).\n   - The consolidated financial statements (which combine all segments) would show the **eliminated intersegment balances** in the consolidation process, but these eliminations are not broken out in the segment-level tables provided.\n\n### Summary of Key Points:\n- **Intersegment Transactions:** Primarily consist of **launch services for Starlink satellites** (Connectivity segment) and potentially for future AI segment needs.\n- **Revenue Recognition:** **No intersegment revenue** is recognized for these launches; costs are **capitalized** into the assets of the receiving segment.\n- **Transfer Pricing Policy:** Based on **cost capitalization**, not market-based pricing or revenue recognition. This ensures that intersegment profits are not recognized until the underlying assets (e.g., satellites) generate external revenue.\n- **Financial Disclosure:** Segment tables show **net segment performance after intersegment eliminations**, with the "Total Reportable Segments" column reflecting the combined results of all segments without intersegment profit or loss.',
